GOAL: 
    - build a simple flask web app(app.py)
    - turn it into a docker container
    - run it in the browser

STEP 1 - CREATE PROJECT FOLDER AND CD INTO IT
    "mkdir flask_project"
    "cd flask_project"
STEP 2 - CREATE YOUR APP
    "touch app.py"
    - OPEN IT AND ADD:
        - "from flask import Flask

            app = Flask(__name__)

            @app.route("/")
            def home():
            return "Hello from Docker!"

            if __name__ == "__main__":
            app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5001)"
    WHAT THIS DOES:
        - creates a web server 
        - / route returns text
        - runs port 5001
STEP 3 - TESTS LOCALLY 
    - "python3 app.py"
    open browser:
    [http://localhost:500]
    if this doesnt work docker wont either 

STEP 4 - CREATE REQUIREMENT FILE 
    "touch requirements.txt"
    add: flask
    WHY THIS MATTERS:
        - docker needs to know what to install 

STEP 5 - CREATE DOCKERFILE 
    "touch Dockerfile"
    add:
    "FROM python:3.8-slim

    WORKDIR /app

    COPY requirements.txt .

    RUN pip install -r requirements.txt

    COPY . .

    EXPOSE 5001

    CMD ["python3", "app.py"]"

    WHAT THIS DOES
        - gets python as base image 
        - sets working directory to the /app folder
        - Installs all Python packages listed in requirements.txt 
        - copies your code from computer into container
        - EXPOSE PORT 5001
        - runs your app when container starts

STEP 6 - BUILD DOCKER IMAGE 
    - "docker build -t flask-app ."

STEP 7 - RUN CONTAINER
    - "docker run -p 5001:5001 flask-app"

STEP 8 - OPEN BROWSER
    - http://localhost:5001
you should see : 
    - Hello from Docker!

WHAT I DID 
    - Built a web app, containerised it and exposed it.
COMMON MISTAKES 
    - Forgot 0.0.0.0
    - wrong port
    - docker not running 
    - didnt rebuild after changes
 
